WEBVTT

1
00:00:03.600 --> 00:00:17.880
Your backtest shows one history, the one that actually
happened. But the market could have dealt those exact same
trades in a thousand different orders. Monte Carlo plays
out all of them, so you see the range of futures, not just
the single lucky path you happened to get.

2
00:00:18.480 --> 00:00:32.280
It's the Monte Carlo lab, in Step three. It takes this
move and replays it thousands of times, reshuffling and
redrawing your trades, then shows you the realistic spread
of where you could end up, and how ugly the drawdown could
get along the way.

3
00:00:32.880 --> 00:00:50.424
There are two flavors. Resample draws your trades with
replacement. It asks, if I keep trading this edge, what is
the full range of outcomes? Shuffle keeps the exact same
trades but reorders them. It asks, same results, did I
just get lucky with the sequence? Because drawdown depends
entirely on order.

4
00:00:51.024 --> 00:01:07.680
The Median Outcome is the honest middle result. Half the
simulations did better, half did worse. It's a far more
trustworthy expected number than your single backtest,
which might be sitting at a lucky extreme. The range
around it shows the realistic spread, so you plan for the
low end, not the average.

5
00:01:08.280 --> 00:01:21.576
Then the number that decides survival. Worst Loss Streak.
The longest run of losers across all of those thousands of
simulations. This is the streak you actually have to
budget for. It's the exact number your Doomsday Budget is
built around.

6
00:01:22.176 --> 00:01:37.080
Set your account's drawdown limit, and the lab tells you
how often a simulated run would breach it. That is your
real risk of ruin, expressed as a percentage. Under five
percent is comfortable. Climbing past twenty means this
move is simply too big for that account.

7
00:01:37.680 --> 00:01:47.760
One backtest can fool you with a single lucky run. A
thousand simulations cannot. This is how you tell a real
edge from a fluke, and then size it so the bad runs never
end you.

8
00:01:48.360 --> 00:01:51.672
Don't trust one history. Trust the thousand that could
have been.
